 democratic and authoritarian political traditions, negotiations about the appropriate broadcast language, and the potential for free press and for freedom of speech. The contributors use examples from countries such as Cambodia, Bulgaria, Iran, Nigeria, and Taiwan to not only provide detailed analysis of regional and/or nation-specific cases of media, but also to identify transnational patterns that help deepen the understanding of the media's role in globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Mass Media. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh1 aBlankson, Isaac A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlankson, Isaac A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBroscheva, Elza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKraidy, Marwan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLengel, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarin, Noemi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDaniel, Drew O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Patrick D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Patrick, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOnwumechili, Chuka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaicheva-Stover, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRampal, Kuldip R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRene Sims, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel